14:39.512 --> 14:46.919 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BENJAMIN GINSBERG: Thanks, Judy.

14:47.019 --> 14:54.494 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to our
occasional series
of conversations about whether
some banks

14:54.594 --> 15:00.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and firms are too big to fail,
and whether
they pose a risk to the
country's financial

15:00.366 --> 15:01.167 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
health.

15:01.267 --> 15:03.102 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
John Yang has our latest
installment.

15:03.202 --> 15:09.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Eight years after the
housing bubble
exploded, investment bank
Goldman Sachs this

15:09.175 --> 15:14.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
week became the last big
institution to settle
with the government for its role
in selling

15:14.413 --> 15:18.251 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
bundles of bad loans to
investors, which led
to the financial crisis.

15:18.351 --> 15:23.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this election year, there is
a lot of talk
about whether too many firms
remain too big

15:23.523 --> 15:27.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to fail and whether the
Dodd-Frank law is
working.

15:27.860 --> 15:32.498 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Lynn Stout is a Cornell
University law professor
who now serves on the Treasury
Department's

15:32.598 --> 15:37.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Financial Research Advisory
Committee. She
has been very critical of
Dodd-Frank, and

15:37.236 --> 15:40.439 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
she joins us now from Ithaca,
New York.

15:40.540 --> 15:42.375 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Professor Stout, thanks for
being with us.

15:42.475 --> 15:47.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Let's start off with that
Goldman Sachs settlement
this week. They have agreed to
pay as much

15:47.914 --> 15:54.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as $5 billion in this settlement
with the
government. What does this say
about accountability

15:54.987 --> 16:00.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now among the big financial
institutions after
the financial crisis?

16:00.226 --> 16:04.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LYNN STOUT, Cornell University:
I'm afraid
the settlement confirms
something that we

16:05.064 --> 16:09.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have suspected for quite a long
time, which
is that it looks like fraudulent
practices

16:09.435 --> 16:14.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were hard-baked into the banking
sector during
2008.

16:14.273 --> 16:19.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, unfortunately, although $5
billion sounds
like a lot of money, the
settlement is actually

16:19.679 --> 16:24.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
relatively small. It's certainly
small compared
to the damage that was done by
these fraudulent

16:24.450 --> 16:28.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
practices, and it's relatively
small compared
to some of the settlements by
some of the

16:28.387 --> 16:31.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other banks, by Citibank and by
Bank of America.

16:31.891 --> 16:37.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, as large as the figure may
seem, I'm afraid
it creates the risk that this
could be business

16:37.930 --> 16:42.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as usual, that, at the end of
the day, Goldman
Sachs may have found these sorts
of fraudulent

16:42.368 --> 16:45.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
practices to overall profitable,
even in light
of the fines.

16:46.072 --> 16:48.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Business as usual,
you say.

16:48.374 --> 16:52.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, Dodd-Frank was supposed to
address all
this. It was the response to all
of this,

16:52.545 --> 16:57.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the financial crisis and what
brought it on.
You say Dodd-Frank isn't
working. Why not?

16:57.950 --> 16:59.819 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What about it isn't working?

16:59.919 --> 17:05.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LYNN STOUT: The basic problem
with Dodd-Frank
is that it created the
appearance of Congress

17:05.124 --> 17:09.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doing something, without that
appearance being
backed up by reality.

17:09.462 --> 17:14.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What the Dodd-Frank Act did
mostly was direct
various regulators at the
Federal Reserve,

17:14.700 --> 17:21.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the FTC, the CFTC to draft
regulations that
were supposed to rein in the
banks. But Dodd-Frank

17:21.240 --> 17:25.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
itself doesn't impose many hard
and fast rules,
and what's happened in all the
years since

17:25.711 --> 17:30.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that the financial industry,
through lobbying,
campaign contributions,
behind-the-scene actions,

17:30.950 --> 17:37.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HAS been very effective at
stymying regulators
from doing anything that really
crimps their

17:37.123 --> 17:38.958 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
style and reins them in.

17:39.058 --> 17:42.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Well, the banks say
that they are,
they are being reined in. The
banks say that

17:42.595 --> 17:47.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their profits are down, that
Dodd-Frank has
changed the way they do
business. They're

17:47.266 --> 17:53.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
holding more capital, they say.
They're being
more closely regulated. There
are things they

17:53.773 --> 17:55.441 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can and they can't do.

17:55.541 --> 17:58.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as I say, it's cutting into
their profits,
they say. What do you say to
that?

17:58.744 --> 18:03.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LYNN STOUT: Well, it's true that
bank profits
are down, but I think we need to
be realistic.

18:03.282 --> 18:08.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the primary reasons is
that the banks
basically lost the faith of
their customers.

18:08.854 --> 18:13.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They damaged their own
reputations and destroyed
much of their own customer base.
Now, some

18:13.292 --> 18:18.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
regulation does play a role. And
right now,
regulators are watching the
banks pretty closely,

18:18.364 --> 18:20.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but the rules are still pretty
flexible.

18:20.733 --> 18:26.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have to be concerned that
in years
that are coming in the future,
the regulators

18:26.505 --> 18:30.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are going to take their eye off
the ball and
we will be back to some of the
same problems

18:30.276 --> 18:36.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in terms of concentrations of
risk and highly
speculative activity that led to
the 2008

18:36.415 --> 18:37.450 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
collapse in the first place.

18:37.550 --> 18:39.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: What do you think
should be done?

18:39.618 --> 18:43.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LYNN STOUT: It's actually very
straightforward.

18:43.356 --> 18:49.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Up until around the year 2000,
we had a bunch
of banking regulations in place,
including

18:49.795 --> 18:55.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Glass-Steagall and rules against
speculative
derivatives trading that had
proven time-tested

18:55.368 --> 19:00.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at keeping banks from taking on
excessive
risks and had been very
effective at keeping

19:00.673 --> 19:03.876 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the financial sector stable and
sound.

19:03.976 --> 19:09.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And most of those laws were
eliminated in
a -- what's turned out to be a
very misbegotten

19:09.882 --> 19:14.887 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
profit of so-called
deregulation. I think
that if we put those rules back
in place,

19:14.987 --> 19:18.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
experience and history suggest
there's no
reason why we can't have a safe,
sound banking

19:19.025 --> 19:20.793 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
sector.

19:20.893 --> 19:25.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's just very hard without some
of the original
regulatory firewalls we used to
have.

19:25.197 --> 19:29.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Glass-Steagall came
out of the
Depression and said you couldn't
-- you couldn't

19:29.301 --> 19:33.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- had to separate commercial
banking and
investment banking.

19:33.639 --> 19:39.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The critics of that, of your
assessment, say
that a lot of what happened in
the financial

19:39.712 --> 19:44.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crisis had nothing to do with
that. It had
to do with a pure investment
bank like Goldman

19:44.917 --> 19:50.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sachs. It had to do not with the
mixing of
the two. What's your response?

19:50.122 --> 19:55.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LYNN STOUT: Oh, that's true, to
some extent,
but Glass-Steagall wasn't the
only rule that

19:55.828 --> 19:57.763 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was changed.

19:57.863 --> 20:02.068 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
We also legalized
over-the-counter derivatives
for the first time, and we even
gave a derivatives

20:02.168 --> 20:06.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
contracts priority in
bankruptcy. There were
lots and lots of financial rules
that were

20:06.539 --> 20:11.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
changed in favor of the
financial industry
through a steady process of the
application

20:11.811 --> 20:15.381 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of campaign contributions and
lobbying power.

20:15.481 --> 20:20.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if we're going to have a
stable system,
I think we need to find a way to
get past

20:20.519 --> 20:25.257 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
this problem of lack of a
political will to
effectively regulate financial
institutions.

20:25.357 --> 20:29.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: We had Barney Frank
on in one of
our conversations about this,
the Barney Frank

20:29.929 --> 20:31.697 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Dodd-Frank.

20:31.797 --> 20:35.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said that even if an
institution were
to get into trouble, that the
way the law

20:35.201 --> 20:40.339 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is now, there would be no
government bailout,
no propping up of an
institution, it would

20:40.439 --> 20:47.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have to fail, and that whatever
government
funds would be spent would be
spent on letting

20:47.680 --> 20:53.619 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
it dissolve in an orderly
fashion, so it wouldn't
cause a big financial problem to
the rest

20:53.719 --> 20:58.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the economy, and that any
money the government
spent would have to be
recovered.

20:58.724 --> 21:00.226 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Your response.

21:00.326 --> 21:05.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LYNN STOUT: I think that's,
shall we say,
an extremely optimistic view.

21:05.598 --> 21:10.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think history has shown
that the ties
between the big financial
institutions and

21:10.102 --> 21:15.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Washington are so tight that the
financial
institutions are very good at
engineering

21:15.875 --> 21:17.409 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
taxpayer-financed bailouts.

21:17.510 --> 21:24.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Lynn Stout, thanks
for joining
us. Thank you very much.

