36:08.433 --> 36:12.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Making her second
run, Hillary
Clinton is far from the first
woman to set

36:12.837 --> 36:19.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
her eyes on the nation's highest
office. She
follows more than 200 American
women in that

36:19.210 --> 36:21.079 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
quest.

36:21.179 --> 36:35.627 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Take the first, Victoria
Woodhull. The 32-year-old
launched her bid in 1870, almost
half-a-century

36:35.727 --> 36:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a group she organized. Woodhull
faced opposition
in the press, depicted as a
devil for supporting

36:42.600 --> 36:49.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the free love movement, by which
she meant
the freedom to marry, divorce
and bear children.

36:49.340 --> 36:55.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Almost 100 years later came
Maine's Margaret
Chase Smith, the first woman to
be elected

36:55.280 --> 37:00.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into the Senate in her own
right. At President
John F. Kennedy's last press
conference in

37:01.086 --> 37:05.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
