proud of that.

38:30.942 --> 38:32.210 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

38:32.310 --> 38:36.514 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHIRLEY CHISHOLM: I am the
candidate of the
people of America.

38:36.614 --> 38:38.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

38:38.116 --> 38:42.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: These women
helped set the
stage for Hillary Clinton.

38:42.720 --> 38:49.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Already, Clinton has made it
further than
any woman before her. Historian
Ellen Fitzpatrick

38:49.494 --> 38:54.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
profiles the three who laid the
groundwork
for Clinton in her new book,
"The Highest

38:54.999 --> 38:58.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Glass Ceiling: Women's Quest for
the American
Presidency."

38:59.003 --> 39:01.005 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Ellen Fitzpatrick, welcome.

39:01.105 --> 39:01.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLEN FITZPATRICK, Author, "The
Highest Glass
Ceiling: Women's Quest for the
American Presidency":

39:01.839 --> 39:03.641 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thank you. Nice to be here.

39:03.741 --> 39:06.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, there have
been a lot of
books written about women in
politics, but

39:06.344 --> 39:12.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you specifically wanted to focus
on women
going after the top job, the
presidency. Why?

39:12.383 --> 39:16.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLEN FITZPATRICK: Well, there
had been very
little, I noticed, done on this
subject. There

39:16.354 --> 39:22.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had been a lot of books about
the idea of
a woman president, but no
historian had really

39:22.560 --> 39:25.730 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
looked at this question, no
academic historian.

39:25.830 --> 39:31.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It had sort of fallen between
the crevices.
On the one hand, there's so much
presidential

39:31.402 --> 39:35.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
history. On the other hand,
there's a lot
of wonderful work in women's
history. But

39:35.573 --> 39:39.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
women presidential candidates
had largely
been shunted aside.

39:39.510 --> 39:44.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Hillary Clinton,
right now,
she is the front-runner for the
Democratic

39:44.649 --> 39:46.384 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
nomination.

39:46.484 --> 39:51.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the three women you focus on
were women
who, because of the time they
went for the

39:51.422 --> 39:56.494 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
presidency, it was a very
different environment.
Why did you pick these three?

39:56.594 --> 39:58.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And start with Victoria
Woodhull, 1872.

39:58.963 --> 40:00.898 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ELLEN FITZPATRICK: Remarkable.

40:00.999 --> 40:07.105 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
She emerged during
Reconstruction, which was
the period after the Civil War
when many questions

40:07.205 --> 40:13.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were being raised about what
freedom and democracy
in America really meant. We had
just fought

40:13.378 --> 40:19.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this brutal and bloody Civil
War, and in the
aftermath of it, there were four
million slaves

40:19.584 --> 40:27.025 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
emancipated and new
constitutional amendments
written to confer new rights on
African-Americans.

40:27.125 --> 40:33.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In that moment, the suffrage
movement began
to make its claim that women
should be included

40:33.264 --> 40:38.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in these new liberties, that
women's voting
rights should be established.
And Victoria

40:38.136 --> 40:45.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Woodhull emerged in the middle
of that debate
and said: Why not run for the
office itself?

40:45.376 --> 40:48.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I can embody the cause of
women's equality.

40:48.880 --> 40:53.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And then it was
almost another
100 years before another woman
you look at

40:53.951 --> 40:58.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- that was Margaret Chase Smith
-- had been
the senator from the state of
Maine -- she

40:58.389 --> 41:05.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was a Republican -- went for the
presidency.
But she was also facing very,
very tough odds.

41:05.897 --> 41:11.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLEN FITZPATRICK: What was
extraordinary
was to find out, in 1964, the
kinds of things

41:11.469 --> 41:16.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
said about Margaret Chase Smith,
who arguably
was really the best prepared of
any woman

41:16.974 --> 41:23.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who had run, certainly to that
point, were
actually more sexist than what
was being said

41:23.514 --> 41:26.718 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about Victoria Woodhull in 1870.

41:26.818 --> 41:31.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was depicted as, on the one
hand, she
had been greatly admired. As
soon as she announced

41:31.789 --> 41:38.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
